Given, $$\cot ^{-1}(\sqrt{\cos \alpha})-\tan ^{-1} \sqrt{\cos \alpha}=x$$ ... (i)
We know that $$\cot ^{-1}(\sqrt{\cos } \alpha)+\tan ^{-1} \sqrt{\cos \alpha}=\frac{\pi}{2}$$ .... (ii)
On adding Eqs. (i) and (ii), we get
$$\begin{aligned}
& 2 \cot ^{-1} \sqrt{\cos \alpha}=\frac{\pi}{2}+x \\
& \Rightarrow \sqrt{\cos } \alpha=\cot \left(\frac{\pi}{4}+\frac{x}{2}\right)=\frac{\cot \frac{x}{2}-1}{1+\cot \frac{x}{2}}
\end{aligned}$$
$$\Rightarrow \sqrt{\cos \alpha}=\frac{\cos \frac{x}{2}-\sin \frac{x}{2}}{\cos \frac{x}{2}+\sin \frac{x}{2}}$$
On squaring both sides, we get
$$\cos \alpha=\frac{\cos ^2 \frac{x}{2}+\sin ^2 \frac{x}{2}-2 \sin \frac{x}{2} \cos \frac{x}{2}}{\cos ^2 \frac{x}{2}+\sin ^2 \frac{x}{2}+2 \sin \frac{x}{2} \cos \frac{x}{2}}$$
$$\begin{aligned}
& \Rightarrow \cos \alpha=\frac{1-\sin x}{1+\sin x} \\
& \Rightarrow \frac{1-\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}}{1+\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}}=\frac{1-\sin x}{1+\sin x}
\end{aligned}$$
On applying componendo and dividendo rule, we get
$$\begin{aligned}
& \frac{1-\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}-1-\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}}{1-\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}+1+\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}}=\frac{1-\sin x-1-\sin x}{1-\sin x+1+\sin x} \\
\Rightarrow \quad & \tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}=\sin x \\
\Rightarrow \quad & \sin x=\tan ^2 \frac{\alpha}{2}
\end{aligned}$$

